In cases where the hazard requires a response that is unique and not covered by other elements, the plans contain certain hazard-specific information.  Procedures for responding to the following emergencies are included in VenocoÂ¿s  response procedures: 

a)	Hazardous substance spill or release of flammable or toxic liquids or gases;
b)	Fires;
c)	Personnel injuries;
d)	H2S releases;
e)	Storm drain or sewer spill incidents; and
f)	Bomb threats.

VenocoÂ¿s emergency response procedures serve as a guide for company incident response personnel, facility response personnel, spill containment and clean-up contractors and public agencies that may be called upon to respond in controlling an emergency within the facility and surrounding areas. These procedures include employee notification of emergencies and evacuation procedures for all emergency situations.  

1.9 Planned Changes to Improve Safety

The company continually evaluates facility operations and emergency preparedness to identify hazards to its employees or the public and to take reasonable and prudent steps to ensure the safety of its employees and the public. 
1.10 Documents Incorporated by Reference

The following documents are the basis for the RMP program and are incorporated by reference:

1.	Venoco Management of Change Program, October 2007.

2.	Hazardous Materials Business Plan South Ellwood Field, December 2008.

3.	Venoco Fire Prevention and Preparedness Plan South Ellwood Field, October 2008.

4.	Venoco Safety Inspection, Maintenance and Quality Assurance Program, December 2007.

5.	Venoco Incident Prevention Plan, March 2009.

6.	SPCC Plan for the Ellwood Facility, November 2004.

7.	Venoco Ellwood Facility Security Plan, December 2003.

8.	Emergency Action Plan South Ellwood Field, June 2008
